# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nonlinear-regression
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] For linear-algebraic analysis of data, "fitting" usually means trying to find the curve that minimizes the vertical (*y*-axis) displacement of a point from the curve (e.g., ordinary least squares).
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] However, for graphical and image applications, geometric fitting seeks to provide the best visual fit; which usually means trying to minimize the orthogonal distance to the curve (e.g., total least squares), or to otherwise include both axes of displacement of a point from the curve.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Geometric fits are not popular because they usually require non-linear and/or iterative calculations, although they have the advantage of a more aesthetic and geometrically accurate result.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Most commonly, one fits a function of the form *y*=*f*(*x*).
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] A line will connect any two points, so a first degree polynomial equation is an exact fit through any two points with distinct x coordinates.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] This will exactly fit a simple curve to three points.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] A more general statement would be to say it will exactly fit four **constraints**.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Each constraint can be a point, angle, or curvature (which is the reciprocal of the radius of an osculating circle).
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Angle and curvature constraints are most often added to the ends of a curve, and in such cases are called **end conditions**.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Identical end conditions are frequently used to ensure a smooth transition between polynomial curves contained within a single spline.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Higher-order constraints, such as "the change in the rate of curvature", could also be added.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] This, for example, would be useful in highway cloverleaf design to understand the rate of change of the forces applied to a car (see jerk), as it follows the cloverleaf, and to set reasonable speed limits, accordingly.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The first degree polynomial equation could also be an exact fit for a single point and an angle while the third degree polynomial equation could also be an exact fit for two points, an angle constraint, and a curvature constraint.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Many other combinations of constraints are possible for these and for higher order polynomial equations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] If there are more than *n* + 1 constraints (*n* being the degree of the polynomial), the polynomial curve can still be run through those constraints.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] An exact fit to all constraints is not certain (but might happen, for example, in the case of a first degree polynomial exactly fitting three collinear points).
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] In general, however, some method is then needed to evaluate each approximation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The least squares method is one way to compare the deviations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The degree of the polynomial curve being higher than needed for an exact fit is undesirable for all the reasons listed previously for high order polynomials, but also leads to a case where there are an infinite number of solutions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] For example, a first degree polynomial (a line) constrained by only a single point, instead of the usual two, would give an infinite number of solutions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] This brings up the problem of how to compare and choose just one solution, which can be a problem for both software and humans.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Because of this, it is usually best to choose as low a degree as possible for an exact match on all constraints, and perhaps an even lower degree, if an approximate fit is acceptable.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Other types of curves, such as trigonometric functions (such as sine and cosine), may also be used, in certain cases.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] In spectroscopy, data may be fitted with Gaussian, Lorentzian, Voigt and related functions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] In biology, ecology, demography, epidemiology, and many other disciplines, the growth of a population, the spread of infectious disease, etc. can be fitted using the logistic function.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] In agriculture the inverted logistic sigmoid function (S-curve) is used to describe the relation between crop yield and growth factors.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The blue figure was made by a sigmoid regression of data measured in farm lands.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] It can be seen that initially, i.e. at low soil salinity, the crop yield reduces slowly at increasing soil salinity, while thereafter the decrease progresses faster.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] If a function of the form $y=f(x)$ cannot be postulated, one can still try to fit a plane curve.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Other types of curves, such as conic sections (circular, elliptical, parabolic, and hyperbolic arcs) or trigonometric functions (such as sine and cosine), may also be used, in certain cases.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] For example, trajectories of objects under the influence of gravity follow a parabolic path, when air resistance is ignored.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Hence, matching trajectory data points to a parabolic curve would make sense.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Tides follow sinusoidal patterns, hence tidal data points should be matched to a sine wave, or the sum of two sine waves of different periods, if the effects of the Moon and Sun are both considered.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] For a parametric curve, it is effective to fit each of its coordinates as a separate function of arc length; assuming that data points can be ordered, the chord distance may be used.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Coope approaches the problem of trying to find the best visual fit of circle to a set of 2D data points.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The method elegantly transforms the ordinarily non-linear problem into a linear problem that can be solved without using iterative numerical methods, and is hence much faster than previous techniques.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] for points with Cartesian coordinates (x,y) on the border.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] For a data set of scattered points (xi,yi) and a fixed ellipse the right hand sides of this equation are no longer zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] One approach of fitting the points to an ellipse is to find the six parameters A to F such that the sum of the (squares of) the residual right hand sides is minimized.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] This leads to a linear least-squares fitting problem which is basically solved by finding eigenvectors of an associated 6 x 6 matrix which contains sums of mixed powers of (xi,yi).
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The above technique is extended to general ellipses by adding a non-linear step, resulting in a method that is fast, yet finds visually pleasing ellipses of arbitrary orientation and displacement.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] The geometric fit minimizes the sum of the squared orthogonal distances of the data points to the border of the ellipse.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] A similar method that approximates these orthogonal distances is based on the Sampson metric.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Note that while this discussion was in terms of 2D curves, much of this logic also extends to 3D surfaces, each patch of which is defined by a net of curves in two parametric directions, typically called **u** and **v**.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] A surface may be composed of one or more surface patches in each direction.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] Many statistical packages such as R and numerical software such as the gnuplot, GNU Scientific Library, Igor Pro, MLAB, Maple, MATLAB, TK Solver 6.0, Scilab, Mathematica, GNU Octave, and SciPy include commands for doing curve fitting in a variety of scenarios.
[src:nonlinear-regression/curve-fitting] There are also programs specifically written to do curve fitting; they can be found in the lists of statistical and numerical-analysis programs as well as in Category:Regression and curve fitting software.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] The **Gauss–Newton algorithm** is used to solve non-linear least squares problems, which is equivalent to minimizing a sum of squared function values.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] It is an extension of Newton's method for finding a minimum of a non-linear function.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] Since a sum of squares must be nonnegative, the algorithm can be viewed as using Newton's method to iteratively approximate zeroes of the components of the sum, and thus minimizing the sum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] In this sense, the algorithm is also an effective method for solving overdetermined systems of equations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] It has the advantage that second derivatives, which can be challenging to compute, are not required.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] Non-linear least squares problems arise, for instance, in non-linear regression, where parameters in a model are sought such that the model is in good agreement with available observations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] The method is named after the mathematicians Carl Friedrich Gauss and Isaac Newton, and first appeared in Gauss's 1809 work *Theoria motus corporum coelestium in sectionibus conicis solem ambientum*.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] and the symbol $^{\operatorname {T} }$ denotes the matrix transpose.
[src:nonlinear-regression/gauss-newton-algorithm] which is a direct generalization of Newton's method in one dimension.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In regression analysis, **least squares** is a method to determine the best-fit model by minimizing the sum of the squared residuals—the differences between observed values and the values predicted by the model.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Least squares problems fall into two categories: linear or ordinary least squares and nonlinear least squares, depending on whether or not the model functions are linear in all unknowns.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The linear least-squares problem occurs in statistical regression analysis; it has a closed-form solution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The nonlinear problem is usually solved by iterative refinement; at each iteration the system is approximated by a linear one, and thus the core calculation is similar in both cases.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Polynomial least squares describes the variance in a prediction of the dependent variable as a function of the independent variable and the deviations from the fitted curve.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] When the observations come from an exponential family with identity as its natural sufficient statistics and mild-conditions are satisfied (e.g. for normal, exponential, Poisson and binomial distributions), standardized least-squares estimates and maximum-likelihood estimates are identical.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The method of least squares can also be derived as a method of moments estimator.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The first clear and concise exposition of the method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The technique is described as an algebraic procedure for fitting linear equations to data and Legendre demonstrates the new method by analyzing the same data as Laplace for the shape of the Earth.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Within ten years after Legendre's publication, the method of least squares had been adopted as a standard tool in astronomy and geodesy in France, Italy, and Prussia, which constitutes an extraordinarily rapid acceptance of a scientific technique.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In 1809 Carl Friedrich Gauss published his method of calculating the orbits of celestial bodies.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In that work he claimed to have been in possession of the method of least squares since 1795.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] This naturally led to a priority dispute with Legendre.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] However, to Gauss's credit, he went beyond Legendre and succeeded in connecting the method of least squares with the principles of probability and to the normal distribution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] He had managed to complete Laplace's program of specifying a mathematical form of the probability density for the observations, depending on a finite number of unknown parameters, and define a method of estimation that minimizes the error of estimation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Gauss showed that the arithmetic mean is indeed the best estimate of the location parameter by changing both the probability density and the method of estimation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] He then turned the problem around by asking what form the density should have and what method of estimation should be used to get the arithmetic mean as estimate of the location parameter.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In this attempt, he invented the normal distribution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] An early demonstration of the strength of Gauss's method came when it was used to predict the future location of the newly discovered asteroid Ceres.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] On 1 January 1801, the Italian astronomer Giuseppe Piazzi discovered Ceres and was able to track its path for 40 days before it was lost in the glare of the Sun.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Based on these data, astronomers desired to determine the location of Ceres after it emerged from behind the Sun without solving Kepler's complicated nonlinear equations of planetary motion.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The only predictions that successfully allowed Hungarian astronomer Franz Xaver von Zach to relocate Ceres were those performed by the 24-year-old Gauss using least-squares analysis.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In 1810, after reading Gauss's work, Laplace, after proving the central limit theorem, used it to give a large sample justification for the method of least squares and the normal distribution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] An extended version of this result is known as the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The idea of least-squares analysis was also independently formulated by the American Robert Adrain in 1808.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In the next two centuries workers in the theory of errors and in statistics found many different ways of implementing least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The objective consists of adjusting the parameters of a model function to best fit a data set.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A simple data set consists of *n* points (data pairs) $(x_{i},y_{i})\!$ , *i* = 1, …, *n*, where $x_{i}\!$ is an independent variable and $y_{i}\!$ is a dependent variable whose value is found by observation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The model function has the form $f(x,{\boldsymbol {\beta }})$ , where *m* adjustable parameters are held in the vector ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The goal is to find the parameter values for the model that "best" fits the data.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In the simplest case, $f(x_{i},{\boldsymbol {\beta }})={\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ and the result of the least-squares method is the arithmetic mean of the input data.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] An example of a model in two dimensions is that of the straight line.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Denoting the y-intercept as $\beta _{0}$ and the slope as $\beta _{1}$ , the model function is given by $f(x,{\boldsymbol {\beta }})=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] See linear least squares for a fully worked out example of this model.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A data point may consist of more than one independent variable.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] For example, when fitting a plane to a set of height measurements, the plane is a function of two independent variables, *x* and *z*, say.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In the most general case there may be one or more independent variables and one or more dependent variables at each data point.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] To the right is a residual plot illustrating random fluctuations about $r_{i}=0$ , indicating that a linear model $(Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x_{i}+U_{i})$ is appropriate. $U_{i}$ is an independent, random variable.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] If the residual points had some sort of a shape and were not randomly fluctuating, a linear model would not be appropriate.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] For example, if the residual plot had a parabolic shape as seen to the right, a parabolic model $(Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x_{i}+\beta _{2}x_{i}^{2}+U_{i})$ would be appropriate for the data.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] This regression formulation considers only observational errors in the dependent variable (but the alternative total least squares regression can account for errors in both variables).
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The minimum of the sum of squares is found by setting the gradient to zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The gradient equations apply to all least squares problems.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Each particular problem requires particular expressions for the model and its partial derivatives.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A regression model is a linear one when the model comprises a linear combination of the parameters, i.e., $f(x,{\boldsymbol {\beta }})=\sum _{j=1}^{m}\beta _{j}\phi _{j}(x),$ where the function $\phi _{j}$ is a function of x .
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Letting $X_{ij}=\phi _{j}(x_{i})$ and putting the independent and dependent variables in matrices X and $Y,$ respectively, we can compute the least squares in the following way.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] There is, in some cases, a closed-form solution to a non-linear least squares problem – but in general there is not.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In the case of no closed-form solution, numerical algorithms are used to find the value of the parameters $\beta$ that minimizes the objective.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Most algorithms involve choosing initial values for the parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Then, the parameters are refined iteratively, that is, the values are obtained by successive approximation: ${\beta _{j}}^{k+1}={\beta _{j}}^{k}+\Delta \beta _{j},$ where a superscript *k* is an iteration number, and the vector of increments $\Delta \beta _{j}$ is called the shift vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The Jacobian **J** is a function of constants, the independent variable *and* the parameters, so it changes from one iteration to the next.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] These are the defining equations of the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] These differences must be considered whenever the solution to a nonlinear least squares problem is being sought.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Consider a simple example drawn from physics.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A spring should obey Hooke's law which states that the extension of a spring y is proportional to the force, *F*, applied to it. $y=f(F,k)=kF$ constitutes the model, where *F* is the independent variable.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In order to estimate the force constant, *k*, we conduct a series of *n* measurements with different forces to produce a set of data, $(F_{i},y_{i}),\ i=1,\dots ,n\!$ , where *yi* is a measured spring extension.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] There are many methods we might use to estimate the unknown parameter *k*.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Since the *n* equations in the *m* variables in our data comprise an overdetermined system with one unknown and *n* equations, we estimate *k* using least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] We assume that applying force *causes* the spring to expand.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] After having derived the force constant by least squares fitting, we predict the extension from Hooke's law.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The denominator, *n* − *m*, is the statistical degrees of freedom; see effective degrees of freedom for generalizations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] If the probability distribution of the parameters is known or an asymptotic approximation is made, confidence limits can be found.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Similarly, statistical tests on the residuals can be conducted if the probability distribution of the residuals is known or assumed.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] We can derive the probability distribution of any linear combination of the dependent variables if the probability distribution of experimental errors is known or assumed.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Inferring is easy when assuming that the errors follow a normal distribution, consequently implying that the parameter estimates and residuals will also be normally distributed conditional on the values of the independent variables.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] It is necessary to make assumptions about the nature of the experimental errors to test the results statistically.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A common assumption is that the errors belong to a normal distribution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The central limit theorem supports the idea that this is a good approximation in many cases.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] However, suppose the errors are not normally distributed.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In that case, a central limit theorem often nonetheless implies that the parameter estimates will be approximately normally distributed so long as the sample is reasonably large.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] For this reason, given the important property that the error mean is independent of the independent variables, the distribution of the error term is not an important issue in regression analysis.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Specifically, it is not typically important whether the error term follows a normal distribution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] A special case of generalized least squares called **weighted least squares** occurs when all the off-diagonal entries of Ω (the correlation matrix of the residuals) are null; the variances of the observations (along the covariance matrix diagonal) may still be unequal (heteroscedasticity).
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In simpler terms, heteroscedasticity is when the variance of $Y_{i}$ depends on the value of $x_{i}$ which causes the residual plot to create a "fanning out" effect towards larger or smaller $Y_{i}$ values as seen in the residual plot to the right.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] On the other hand, homoscedasticity is assuming that the variance of $Y_{i}$ and variance of $U_{i}$ are equal.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The first principal component about the mean of a set of points can be represented by that line which most closely approaches the data points (as measured by squared distance of closest approach, i.e. perpendicular to the line).
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In contrast, linear least squares tries to minimize the distance in the y direction only.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Thus, although the two use a similar error metric, linear least squares is a method that treats one dimension of the data preferentially, while PCA treats all dimensions equally.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Notable statistician Sara van de Geer used empirical process theory and the Vapnik–Chervonenkis dimension to prove a least-squares estimator can be interpreted as a measure on the space of square-integrable functions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In some contexts, a regularized version of the least squares solution may be preferable.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Tikhonov regularization (or ridge regression) adds a constraint that $\left\|\beta \right\|_{2}^{2}$ , the squared $\ell _{2}$ -norm of the parameter vector, is not greater than a given value to the least squares formulation, leading to a constrained minimization problem.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] This is equivalent to the unconstrained minimization problem where the objective function is the residual sum of squares plus a penalty term $\alpha \left\|\beta \right\|_{2}^{2}$ and $\alpha$ is a tuning parameter (this is the Lagrangian form of the constrained minimization problem).
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] In a Bayesian context, this is equivalent to placing a zero-mean normally distributed prior on the parameter vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] An alternative regularized version of least squares is Lasso (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator), which uses the constraint that $\|\beta \|_{1}$ , the L1-norm of the parameter vector, is no greater than a given value.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] (One can show like above using Lagrange multipliers that this is equivalent to an unconstrained minimization of the least-squares penalty with $\alpha \|\beta \|_{1}$ added.) In a Bayesian context, this is equivalent to placing a zero-mean Laplace prior distribution on the parameter vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The optimization problem may be solved using quadratic programming or more general convex optimization methods, as well as by specific algorithms such as the least angle regression algorithm.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] One of the prime differences between Lasso and ridge regression is that in ridge regression, as the penalty is increased, all parameters are reduced while still remaining non-zero, while in Lasso, increasing the penalty will cause more and more of the parameters to be driven to zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] This is an advantage of Lasso over ridge regression, as driving parameters to zero deselects the features from the regression.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Thus, Lasso automatically selects more relevant features and discards the others, whereas Ridge regression never fully discards any features.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] Some feature selection techniques are developed based on the LASSO including Bolasso which bootstraps samples, and FeaLect which analyzes the regression coefficients corresponding to different values of $\alpha$ to score all the features.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] The *L*1-regularized formulation is useful in some contexts due to its tendency to prefer solutions where more parameters are zero, which gives solutions that depend on fewer variables.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] For this reason, the Lasso and its variants are fundamental to the field of compressed sensing.
[src:nonlinear-regression/least-squares] An extension of this approach is elastic net regularization.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] In mathematics and computing, the **Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm** (**LMA** or just **LM**), also known as the **damped least-squares** (**DLS**) method, is used to solve non-linear least squares problems.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] These minimization problems arise especially in least squares curve fitting.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The LMA interpolates between the Gauss–Newton algorithm (GNA) and the method of gradient descent.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The LMA is more robust than the GNA, which means that in many cases it finds a solution even if it starts very far off the final minimum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] For well-behaved functions and reasonable starting parameters, the LMA tends to be slower than the GNA.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] LMA can also be viewed as Gauss–Newton using a trust region approach.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The algorithm was first published in 1944 by Kenneth Levenberg, while working at the Frankford Army Arsenal.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] It was rediscovered in 1963 by Donald Marquardt, who worked as a statistician at DuPont, and independently by Girard, Wynne and Morrison.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The LMA is used in many software applications for solving generic curve-fitting problems.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] By using the Gauss–Newton algorithm it often converges faster than first-order methods.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] However, like other iterative optimization algorithms, the LMA finds only a local minimum, which is not necessarily the global minimum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Like other numeric minimization algorithms, the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm is an iterative procedure.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] To start a minimization, the user has to provide an initial guess for the parameter vector ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] In each iteration step, the parameter vector ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠ is replaced by a new estimate ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}+{\boldsymbol {\delta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] where $\mathbf {J} _{i}={\frac {\partial f{\left(x_{i},{\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)}}{\partial {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}}$ is the gradient (row-vector in this case) of ⁠ f ⁠ with respect to ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The sum $S\left({\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)$ of square deviations has its minimum at a zero gradient with respect to ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] where $\mathbf {J}$ is the Jacobian matrix, whose ⁠ i ⁠-th row equals $\mathbf {J} _{i}$ , and where $\mathbf {f} \left({\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)$ and $\mathbf {y}$ are vectors with ⁠ i ⁠-th component $f\left(x_{i},{\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)$ and $y_{i}$ respectively.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The above expression obtained for ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠ comes under the Gauss–Newton method.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The Jacobian matrix as defined above is not (in general) a square matrix, but a rectangular matrix of size $m\times n$ , where n is the number of parameters (size of the vector ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ).
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The matrix multiplication $\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {J} \right)$ yields the required $n\times n$ square matrix and the matrix-vector product on the right hand side yields a vector of size n .
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The result is a set of n linear equations, which can be solved for ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\delta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] where ⁠ $\mathbf {I}$ ⁠ is the identity matrix, giving as the increment ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\delta }}$ ⁠ to the estimated parameter vector ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The (non-negative) damping factor ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ is adjusted at each iteration.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] If reduction of ⁠ S ⁠ is rapid, a smaller value can be used, bringing the algorithm closer to the Gauss–Newton algorithm, whereas if an iteration gives insufficient reduction in the residual, ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠ can be increased, giving a step closer to the gradient-descent direction.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Note that the gradient of ⁠ S ⁠ with respect to ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ⁠ equals $-2\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathrm {T} }\left[\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {f} {\left({\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)}\right]\right)^{\mathrm {T} }$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Therefore, for large values of ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠, the step will be taken approximately in the direction opposite to the gradient.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] To make the solution scale invariant Marquardt's algorithm solved a modified problem with each component of the gradient scaled according to the curvature.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] This provides larger movement along the directions where the gradient is smaller, which avoids slow convergence in the direction of small gradient.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] A similar damping factor appears in Tikhonov regularization, which is used to solve linear ill-posed problems, as well as in ridge regression, an estimation technique in statistics.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Various more or less heuristic arguments have been put forward for the best choice for the damping parameter ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Theoretical arguments exist showing why some of these choices guarantee local convergence of the algorithm; however, these choices can make the global convergence of the algorithm suffer from the undesirable properties of steepest descent, in particular, very slow convergence close to the optimum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The absolute values of any choice depend on how well-scaled the initial problem is.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Marquardt recommended starting with a value ⁠ $\lambda _{0}$ ⁠ and a factor ⁠ $\nu >1$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Initially setting $\lambda =\lambda _{0}$ and computing the residual sum of squares $S\left({\boldsymbol {\beta }}\right)$ after one step from the starting point with the damping factor of $\lambda =\lambda _{0}$ and secondly with ⁠ $\lambda _{0}/\nu$ ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] If both of these are worse than the initial point, then the damping is increased by successive multiplication by ⁠ $\nu$ ⁠ until a better point is found with a new damping factor of ⁠ $\lambda _{0}\nu ^{k}$ ⁠ for some ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] An effective strategy for the control of the damping parameter, called *delayed gratification*, consists of increasing the parameter by a small amount for each uphill step, and decreasing by a large amount for each downhill step.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The idea behind this strategy is to avoid moving downhill too fast in the beginning of optimization, therefore restricting the steps available in future iterations and therefore slowing down convergence.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] An increase by a factor of 2 and a decrease by a factor of 3 has been shown to be effective in most cases, while for large problems more extreme values can work better, with an increase by a factor of 1.5 and a decrease by a factor of 5.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] where $f({\boldsymbol {x}})$ and ${\boldsymbol {J}}$ have already been computed by the algorithm, therefore requiring only one additional function evaluation to compute $f({\boldsymbol {x}}+h{\boldsymbol {\delta }})$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The choice of the finite difference step h can affect the stability of the algorithm, and a value of around 0.1 is usually reasonable in general.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] where $\alpha$ is usually fixed to a value lesser than 1, with smaller values for harder problems.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] In this example we try to fit the function $y=a\cos \left(bX\right)+b\sin \left(aX\right)$ using the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm implemented in GNU Octave as the *leasqr* function.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] The graphs show progressively better fitting for the parameters $a=100$ , $b=102$ used in the initial curve.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] Only when the parameters in the last graph are chosen closest to the original, are the curves fitting exactly.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] This equation is an example of very sensitive initial conditions for the Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm.
[src:nonlinear-regression/levenberg-marquardt-algorithm] One reason for this sensitivity is the existence of multiple minima — the function $\cos \left(\beta x\right)$ has minima at parameter value ${\hat {\beta }}$ and ${\hat {\beta }}+2n\pi$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The minimum value of S occurs when the gradient is zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] In a nonlinear system, the derivatives ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial r_{i}}{\partial \beta _{j}}}}$ are functions of both the independent variable and the parameters, so in general these gradient equations do not have a closed solution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Instead, initial values must be chosen for the parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Here, k is an iteration number and the vector of increments, $\Delta {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ is known as the shift vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] These equations form the basis for the Gauss–Newton algorithm for a non-linear least squares problem.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Note the sign convention in the definition of the Jacobian matrix in terms of the derivatives.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Formulas linear in J may appear with factor of $-1$ in other articles or the literature.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Each element of the diagonal weight matrix **W** should, ideally, be equal to the reciprocal of the error variance of the measurement.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] In linear least squares the objective function, S, is a quadratic function of the parameters. $S=\sum _{i}W_{ii}\left(y_{i}-\sum _{j}X_{ij}\beta _{j}\right)^{2}$ When there is only one parameter the graph of S with respect to that parameter will be a parabola.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] With two or more parameters the contours of S with respect to any pair of parameters will be concentric ellipses (assuming that the normal equations matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {WX}$ is positive definite).
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The minimum parameter values are to be found at the centre of the ellipses.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The geometry of the general objective function can be described as paraboloid elliptical.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A consequence of this is that initial parameter estimates should be as close as practicable to their (unknown!) optimal values.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] It also explains how divergence can come about as the Gauss–Newton algorithm is convergent only when the objective function is approximately quadratic in the parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Some problems of ill-conditioning and divergence can be corrected by finding initial parameter estimates that are near to the optimal values.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A good way to do this is by computer simulation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Both the observed and calculated data are displayed on a screen.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The parameters of the model are adjusted by hand until the agreement between observed and calculated data is reasonably good.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Although this will be a subjective judgment, it is sufficient to find a good starting point for the non-linear refinement.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Initial parameter estimates can be created using transformations or linearizations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Better still evolutionary algorithms such as the Stochastic Funnel Algorithm can lead to the convex basin of attraction that surrounds the optimal parameter estimates.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Hybrid algorithms that use randomization and elitism, followed by Newton methods have been shown to be useful and computationally efficient.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Any method among the ones described below can be applied to find a solution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The common sense criterion for convergence is that the sum of squares does not increase from one iteration to the next.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] However this criterion is often difficult to implement in practice, for various reasons.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A useful convergence criterion is $\left|{\frac {S^{k}-S^{k+1}}{S^{k}}}\right|<0.0001.$ The value 0.0001 is somewhat arbitrary and may need to be changed.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] In particular it may need to be increased when experimental errors are large.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Again, the numerical value is somewhat arbitrary; 0.001 is equivalent to specifying that each parameter should be refined to 0.1% precision.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] This is reasonable when it is less than the largest relative standard deviation on the parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] There are models for which it is either very difficult or even impossible to derive analytical expressions for the elements of the Jacobian.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The increment, $\delta \beta _{j}$ , size should be chosen so the numerical derivative is not subject to approximation error by being too large, or round-off error by being too small.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Some information is given in the corresponding section on the Weighted least squares page.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Not all multiple minima have equal values of the objective function.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] False minima, also known as local minima, occur when the objective function value is greater than its value at the so-called global minimum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] To be certain that the minimum found is the global minimum, the refinement should be started with widely differing initial values of the parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] When the same minimum is found regardless of starting point, it is likely to be the global minimum.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] When multiple minima exist there is an important consequence: the objective function will have a stationary point (e.g. a maximum or a saddle point) somewhere between two minima.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The normal equations matrix is not positive definite at a stationary point in the objective function, because the gradient vanishes and no unique direction of descent exists.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Refinement from a point (a set of parameter values) close to a stationary point will be ill-conditioned and should be avoided as a starting point.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] For example, when fitting a Lorentzian the normal equations matrix is not positive definite when the half-width of the Lorentzian is zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A non-linear model can sometimes be transformed into a linear one.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Such an approximation is, for instance, often applicable in the vicinity of the best estimator, and it is one of the basic assumption in most iterative minimization algorithms.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] When a linear approximation is valid, the model can directly be used for inference with a generalized least squares, where the equations of the Linear Template Fit apply.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The sum of squares becomes $S=\sum _{i}(\log y_{i}-\log \alpha -\beta x_{i})^{2}.$ This procedure should be avoided unless the errors are multiplicative and log-normally distributed because it can give misleading results.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] This comes from the fact that whatever the experimental errors on *y* might be, the errors on log *y* are different.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Therefore, when the transformed sum of squares is minimized, different results will be obtained both for the parameter values and their calculated standard deviations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] However, with multiplicative errors that are log-normally distributed, this procedure gives unbiased and consistent parameter estimates.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The normal equations $\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {WJ} \right)\Delta {\boldsymbol {\beta }}=\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {W} \right)\Delta \mathbf {y}$ may be solved for $\Delta {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ by Cholesky decomposition, as described in linear least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The parameters are updated iteratively ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}^{k+1}={\boldsymbol {\beta }}^{k}+\Delta {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ where *k* is an iteration number.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] While this method may be adequate for simple models, it will fail if divergence occurs.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Therefore, protection against divergence is essential.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The fraction, *f* could be optimized by a line search.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] As each trial value of *f* requires the objective function to be re-calculated it is not worth optimizing its value too stringently.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] When using shift-cutting, the direction of the shift vector remains unchanged.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] If divergence occurs and the direction of the shift vector is so far from its "ideal" direction that shift-cutting is not very effective, that is, the fraction, *f* required to avoid divergence is very small, the direction must be changed.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] This can be achieved by using the Marquardt parameter.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] In this method the normal equations are modified $\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {WJ} +\lambda \mathbf {I} \right)\Delta {\boldsymbol {\beta }}=\left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {W} \right)\Delta \mathbf {y}$ where $\lambda$ is the Marquardt parameter and **I** is an identity matrix.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Increasing the value of $\lambda$ has the effect of changing both the direction and the length of the shift vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] So, when $\lambda$ becomes very large, the shift vector becomes a small fraction of the steepest descent vector.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Various strategies have been proposed for the determination of the Marquardt parameter.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] As with shift-cutting, it is wasteful to optimize this parameter too stringently.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Rather, once a value has been found that brings about a reduction in the value of the objective function, that value of the parameter is carried to the next iteration, reduced if possible, or increased if need be.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] When reducing the value of the Marquardt parameter, there is a cut-off value below which it is safe to set it to zero, that is, to continue with the unmodified Gauss–Newton method.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The cut-off value may be set equal to the smallest singular value of the Jacobian.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A bound for this value is given by $1/\operatorname {tr} \left(\mathbf {J} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {WJ} \right)^{-1}$ where tr is the trace function.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The minimum in the sum of squares can be found by a method that does not involve forming the normal equations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The residual vector is left-multiplied by $\mathbf {Q} ^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] This has no effect on the sum of squares since $S=\mathbf {r} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {Q} \mathbf {Q} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r} =\mathbf {r} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {r}$ because **Q** is orthogonal.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The minimum value of *S* is attained when the upper block is zero.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] These equations are easily solved as **R** is upper triangular.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] A variant of the method of orthogonal decomposition involves singular value decomposition, in which **R** is diagonalized by further orthogonal transformations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The relative simplicity of this expression is very useful in theoretical analysis of non-linear least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] The application of singular value decomposition is discussed in detail in Lawson and Hanson.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] There are many examples in the scientific literature where different methods have been used for non-linear data-fitting problems.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] Direct search methods depend on evaluations of the objective function at a variety of parameter values and do not use derivatives at all.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] They offer alternatives to the use of numerical derivatives in the Gauss–Newton method and gradient methods.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-least-squares] More detailed descriptions of these, and other, methods are available, in *Numerical Recipes*, together with computer code in various languages.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] In statistics, **nonlinear regression** is a form of regression analysis in which observational data are modeled by a function which is a nonlinear combination of the model parameters and depends on one or more independent variables.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The data are fitted by a method of successive approximations (iterations).
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] relates a vector of independent variables, $\mathbf {x}$ , and its associated observed dependent variables, $\mathbf {y}$ .
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The function f is nonlinear in the components of the vector of parameters $\beta$ , but otherwise arbitrary.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] This function, which is a rectangular hyperbola, is *nonlinear* because it cannot be expressed as a linear combination of the two $\beta$ s.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Systematic error may be present in the independent variables but its treatment is outside the scope of regression analysis.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] If the independent variables are not error-free, this is an errors-in-variables model, also outside this scope.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Other examples of nonlinear functions include exponential functions, logarithmic functions, trigonometric functions, power functions, Gaussian function, and Lorentz distributions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Some functions, such as the exponential or logarithmic functions, can be transformed so that they are linear.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] When so transformed, standard linear regression can be performed but must be applied with caution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] See § Linearization §§ Transformation, below, for more details.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] In microbiology and biotechnology, nonlinear regression is used to model complex microbial growth kinetics.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] While simple growth follows monoauxic functions (such as the Gompertz or Boltzmann models), multiphasic (polyauxic) growth is modeled using linear combinations of these nonlinear functions.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] In general, there is no closed-form expression for the best-fitting parameters, as there is in linear regression.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Usually numerical optimization algorithms are applied to determine the best-fitting parameters.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Again in contrast to linear regression, there may be many local minima of the function to be optimized and even the global minimum may produce a biased estimate.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] In practice, estimated values of the parameters are used, in conjunction with the optimization algorithm, to attempt to find the global minimum of a sum of squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] For details concerning nonlinear data modeling see least squares and non-linear least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] where $J_{ij}={\frac {\partial f(x_{i},{\boldsymbol {\beta }})}{\partial \beta _{j}}}$ are Jacobian matrix elements.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}\approx \mathbf {(J^{T}J)^{-1}J^{T}y} ,$ compare generalized least squares with covariance matrix proportional to the unit matrix.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The nonlinear regression statistics are computed and used as in linear regression statistics, but using **J** in place of **X** in the formulas.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The linear approximation introduces bias into the statistics.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Therefore, more caution than usual is required in interpreting statistics derived from a nonlinear model.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The best-fit curve is often assumed to be that which minimizes the sum of squared residuals.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] This is the ordinary least squares (OLS) approach.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] However, in cases where the dependent variable does not have constant variance, or there are some outliers, a sum of weighted squared residuals may be minimized; see weighted least squares.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Each weight should ideally be equal to the reciprocal of the variance of the observation, or the reciprocal of the dependent variable to some power in the outlier case, but weights may be recomputed on each iteration, in an iteratively weighted least squares algorithm.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Some nonlinear regression problems can be moved to a linear domain by a suitable transformation of the model formulation.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] with parameters *a* and *b* and with multiplicative error term *U*.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] where *u* = ln(*U*), suggesting estimation of the unknown parameters by a linear regression of ln(*y*) on *x*, a computation that does not require iterative optimization.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] However, use of a nonlinear transformation requires caution.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The influences of the data values will change, as will the error structure of the model and the interpretation of any inferential results.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] On the other hand, depending on what the largest source of error is, a nonlinear transformation may distribute the errors in a Gaussian fashion, so the choice to perform a nonlinear transformation must be informed by modeling considerations.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] of 1/*v* against 1/[*S*] has been much used.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] However, since it is very sensitive to data error and is strongly biased toward fitting the data in a particular range of the independent variable, [*S*], its use is strongly discouraged.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] For error distributions that belong to the exponential family, a link function may be used to transform the parameters under the Generalized linear model framework.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] The *independent* or *explanatory variable* (say X) can be split up into classes or segments and linear regression can be performed per segment.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] Segmented regression with confidence analysis may yield the result that the *dependent* or *response* variable (say Y) behaves differently in the various segments.
[src:nonlinear-regression/nonlinear-regression] For example, the figure shows that the soil salinity (X) initially exerts no influence on the crop yield (Y) of mustard, until a *critical* or *threshold* value (*breakpoint*), after which the yield is affected negatively.
